WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.269 --> 00:00:06.227
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:00:06.227 --> 00:00:07.762
-My name is Andrea Zapata.

00:00:07.762 --> 00:00:09.350
I'm 16 years old.

00:00:09.350 --> 00:00:11.995
I'm from Minnesota, and
I have cystic fibrosis.

00:00:11.995 --> 00:00:13.800
Cystic Fibrosis is
a genetic disease

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:16.880
that makes the secretions
in my body thicker.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:19.860
That's why my lungs and
sinuses get full of mucous

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:21.050
and infected.

00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:23.470
My pancreas doesn't
produce the enzymes

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:25.538
that help to digest my
food and the insulin

00:00:25.538 --> 00:00:28.530
to keep my sugars stable.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:30.840
And my liver gets
full of stones.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:33.450
There's no cure for
cystic fibrosis yet.

00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:35.330
But there's a lot
of treatments that I

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:37.120
have to take to stay healthy.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.235
For example, I have to take
four of these with every meal

00:00:40.235 --> 00:00:42.090
so I digest my food properly.

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:43.710
And these are vitamins.

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:47.310
Some are for my liver, and
for a bunch of other things.

00:00:47.310 --> 00:00:51.650
This is not even a week of
pills that I have to take.

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:52.630
This is my nebulizer.

00:00:52.630 --> 00:00:55.250
I use it from three
to four times a day,

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:57.450
and twice a day with my vest.

00:00:57.450 --> 00:00:59.280
Together they help
me to keep my lungs

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:01.170
clear and without infection.

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:04.470
I also have to get IV
antibiotics from three to four

00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:05.550
times a year.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:08.140
And because my veins don't
work property anymore,

00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:10.960
I recently had to get a
Port-a-Cath implanted, which

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:13.190
is this little bump right here.

00:01:13.190 --> 00:01:16.130
And my mom just puts
a little needle in it,

00:01:16.130 --> 00:01:20.010
and the treatment lasts
from two to three weeks.

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:23.740
Last year, after a rough couple
of months in the hospital,

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:27.280
my doctors introduced
me to Make-A-Wish,

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:28.520
and they helped me to apply.

00:01:28.520 --> 00:01:30.900
I was so shocked
because I couldn't

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:34.020
believe that they could
take my lifetime dream

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:35.570
and make it come true.

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:39.200
A lot of people ask me why
I chose Google as my wish.

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:43.340
It wasn't because the offices
looked cool on the moves.

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:46.890
Google is so much more than
what everyone imagines.

00:01:46.890 --> 00:01:51.110
For me, it was an inspiration
to see the Googlers work hard

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:53.990
every day to make
people's lives easier

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:55.760
with big smiles on their faces.

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:58.760
The adventure has started
here in Venezuela,

00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:00.933
when my family and I
got onto the plane,

00:02:00.933 --> 00:02:04.076
and the pilot came
to my seat and asked

00:02:04.076 --> 00:02:06.750
me to go with him to the cabin.

00:02:06.750 --> 00:02:08.710
He explained to me
how everything works.

00:02:08.710 --> 00:02:12.150
We took selfies, and it
was a really nice surprise.

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:14.380
Make-A-Wish also made
possible for my brother

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:17.300
to go, which made the
experience so much better,

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:19.642
since he's a student in England.

00:02:19.642 --> 00:02:21.920
They let us explore the
whole city of San Francisco,

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:24.910
and we got to see a lot
of wonderful places.

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:27.880
The first place that
we visited was Verb.

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:30.310
I was so confused because I
hadn't heard of that company

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:31.010
before.

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:33.550
But I'm so thankful that I did.

00:02:33.550 --> 00:02:35.760
Ethan, Brian, and
[INAUDIBLE] explained to us

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.670
everything that they
were working on.

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:39.700
And I was so
impressed to see how

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:42.590
they create tools
that fit in perfectly

00:02:42.590 --> 00:02:44.420
within people's health needs.

00:02:44.420 --> 00:02:47.790
I also asked them to keep
cystic fibrosis in mind

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:53.170
because I hope that one day they
can create something to help CF

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:55.230
patients all around the world.

00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:58.960
Then we met Andrew, an amazing
Googler from Google Fit.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:01.760
I had the opportunity to ask him
a few questions about Google,

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:04.590
and he was so pleased
and glad to answer them,

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:06.820
as I was to hear them.

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:11.400
He also gave me some pretty
cool gifts, like Moto 360.

00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:14.010
Right before going to lunch,
we took a lot of pictures

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:15.840
with Stan, the dinosaur.

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:18.180
Then we had lunch
at Charlie's Cafe,

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:21.520
which is the most popular
cafe in Googleplex.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:23.610
I had the best burrito
that I have ever

00:03:23.610 --> 00:03:25.810
had in my entire life.

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:28.360
After this is when I saw
one of the things that

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:31.470
really impressed me,
the conference bicycle.

00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:35.490
It fits six people, and
they have meetings in there,

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:38.153
while riding around campus.

00:03:38.153 --> 00:03:38.880
How cool is that?

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:42.170
Then we met Grace, who
works at the Chrome office.

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:46.330
And besides how great she
was, she gave me a Nexus 5.

00:03:46.330 --> 00:03:47.880
I was so excited.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.220
One of the most unbelievable
things that I saw

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:52.230
was this self-driving car.

00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:56.000
I never imagined that I
would get on one of them.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.210
It was so crazy to
see how well it works.

00:03:59.210 --> 00:04:00.951
Sadly, the day was over.

00:04:00.951 --> 00:04:02.450
We went to Google
merchandise store,

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:08.820
where I got this cooler, this
pen, this mouse pad, and Alisha

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:10.470
gave me this t-shirt.

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:14.020
I have no words to thank
Make-A-Wish, especially

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:17.470
Jessie and Sasha, for
making my wish come true

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:21.110
and letting me enjoy this
wonderful week with my family,

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:27.050
along with Katie and Alicia, and
every single person in Google

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:30.140
who shared their
experiences and time with me

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:32.520
and made it the
best day of my life.

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:36.130
I can't forget to thank
my amazing medical team

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:37.990
at the University of
Miami Cystic Fibrosis

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:41.450
Center-- my doctors, my
nurses, my therapists,

00:04:41.450 --> 00:04:44.485
my social worker, and especially
[? Alisa ?], [INAUDIBLE],

00:04:44.485 --> 00:04:48.960
and Andrew for always helping me
to stay as healthy as possible

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:51.480
and who introduced
me to Make-A-Wish.

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:55.830
I hope that you can keep
making every wish of every kid

00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:58.800
all around the world come
true and you can make

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:01.990
them feel like feel right now.

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:03.870
Now I know that
wishes do come true.

