That's all.

00:06:30.492 --> 00:06:32.200
MATT TARGETT: I was
going to get to that.

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:33.866
So you've been in New
York for 20 years.

00:06:33.866 --> 00:06:36.852
But there's a life before that
that took you to New York City.

00:06:36.852 --> 00:06:38.060
Can you take us through that?

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.560
NIGEL BARKER: Yeah,
well, certainly,

00:06:39.560 --> 00:06:42.680
very quickly, I was a
lucky kind of character.

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:45.790
I think a lot of things happened
for me that sort of set me up

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:48.436
for where I am sort of today.

00:06:48.436 --> 00:06:51.310
I'm a born and bred
Londoner from Chelsea.

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:53.500
But I come from a mixed
background, mixed family.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.541
And I started-- growing
up in the '70s in England

00:06:55.541 --> 00:06:57.570
as part Sri Lankan,
part English,

00:06:57.570 --> 00:06:59.760
I was one of the only
kids that sort of looked

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:00.892
my way in my neighborhood.

00:07:00.892 --> 00:07:03.350
And at the school I went to
there were very few mixed kids.

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:05.600
Of course, now when I look
across almost any audience,

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:08.210
you have a beautiful array
of color and different types.

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:09.710
But that wasn't
the case, certainly

00:07:09.710 --> 00:07:11.092
not in the '70s in London.

00:07:11.092 --> 00:07:12.550
And that was one
of the reasons why

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:15.547
I was very interested
in exploring the world.

00:07:15.547 --> 00:07:16.880
And I know you're an Australian.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:18.546
And Australians love
to travel the world

00:07:18.546 --> 00:07:20.339
and see what the rest
of the world's like.

00:07:20.339 --> 00:07:22.255
I think England's a
similar thing-- an island,

00:07:22.255 --> 00:07:23.860
and people trying
to get off quickly.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:27.570
And certainly, myself,
I always-- who am I?

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:28.680
What am I?

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:32.420
And the fashion world
intrigued me very early on.

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:36.770
At school, I'd been interested
in things like fashion design

00:07:36.770 --> 00:07:38.730
and pattern cutting and
tailoring and weaving

00:07:38.730 --> 00:07:40.340
and photography and art.

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:45.540
Yet I was predisposed to be
better at math, sciences,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:47.540
and so I was going to be
a doctor because that's

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:51.235
what everyone says you
should be because you can be.

00:07:51.235 --> 00:07:52.980
But it wasn't what
interested me.

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.690
And so for me, as
fate would have it,

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:57.470
there was a show on
television in England

00:07:57.470 --> 00:07:58.730
called "The Clothes Show."

00:07:58.730 --> 00:08:00.270
And it's rather an
ironic situation

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:02.728
because it's one of the very
first televised model searches

00:08:02.728 --> 00:08:03.950
ever, in the '80s.

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:05.700
And I didn't win, but
my mother entered me

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:08.880
onto this TV show, which ended
up with me getting a contract

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:11.350
to become a model that I
decided I do for a year

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:13.660
in between medical school,
raise a little bit of money

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:14.680
before going back.

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:15.682
One year lead two.

00:08:15.682 --> 00:08:17.140
Be careful, parents,
what you allow

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:20.490
your kids to do because
financial independence meant

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:22.670
after two years, that when
they said, OK, now you

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:26.850
need to go to school and study
medicine, I said, well, see ya.

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:30.400
And I disappeared into Europe
and hung out in Milan and Paris

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:33.169
and enjoyed that world
and became a photographer

00:08:33.169 --> 00:08:36.380
eventually, when things changed
in the mid-'90s, and I realized

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:39.210
I was not hair and chic
androgynous or ever going to be

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:40.350
a waif model.

00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:45.310
And I didn't want to throw
away the six years of history

00:08:45.310 --> 00:08:46.490
I'd had in modeling, so.

00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:47.190
MATT TARGETT: Interesting.

00:08:47.190 --> 00:08:49.356
So it sort of seems like
your life came full circle.

00:08:49.356 --> 00:08:51.194
Your mother was a
Miss Sri Lanka winner?

00:08:51.194 --> 00:08:52.360
NIGEL BARKER: She was, yeah.

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:56.340
MATT TARGETT: And you just
judged the Miss USA contest.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:08:59.320
NIGEL BARKER: I have been a
judge of many beauty pageants,

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:01.900
one way or another, whether
it's modeling or you

00:09:01.900 --> 00:09:06.370
"The Face" with Naomi Campbell,
"Top Model" with Tyra,

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:10.090
obviously, Miss Universe
with the Donald.

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:13.480
And I've recently done Miss
USA, Miss World, you name it.

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:15.490
If there's been a
pageant, I think

00:09:15.490 --> 00:09:18.360
I might be the most
qualified beauty pageant

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:21.440
judge in the world, if
that's an actual title.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:22.850
I think I've done
more than most,

00:09:22.850 --> 00:09:24.900
which is really weird
because it's not actually

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.840
not how my mind thinks
or how I like to operate.

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:30.150
I'm not really a
judgemental guy.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:31.430
But one way or the other.

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:32.639
I've been involved with that.

00:09:32.639 --> 00:09:34.263
MATT TARGETT: That's
super interesting.

00:09:34.263 --> 00:09:36.590
And I imagine "America's
Next Top Model," 17 seasons,

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:39.220
was a real career accelerator
that allowed you to do that.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:39.730
NIGEL BARKER: It's funny.

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:41.640
It's one of those things--
yes, absolutely, right.

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:43.090
It was a risk
thought at the time,

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:44.190
and I think that
that's what's something

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:45.390
that people don't often see.

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:47.760
You often look at things
with hindsight, like, OK,

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:49.309
that was obviously a good idea.

00:09:49.309 --> 00:09:50.350
Well done for doing that.

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:53.390
I didn't know it was necessarily
a brilliant idea at the time.

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:56.430
It was a risk, and
I'll tell you why.

00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:59.830
Back then, when I first got
involved with "Top Model,"

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:02.045
the show was on a
small network, UPN,

00:10:02.045 --> 00:10:04.360
that doesn't exist anymore.

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:06.636
Fashion was extremely
elite and exclusive.

00:10:06.636 --> 00:10:08.010
And it was all
about the "Vogues"

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:10.600
and the "Harper's Bazaars"
and the big designers.

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:13.890
And to leave that world
to go on primetime

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:16.610
was a huge commercial
step, and I was sort of

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:18.160
at the brink of
a sort of moments

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:19.800
in my career which
were up and coming.

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:21.520
And big designers
were calling me.

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:23.170
Jil Sander of Versace
was getting a lot

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:24.930
of big breaks in editorial.

00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:26.290
And so it was a risk.

00:10:26.290 --> 00:10:29.855
However, as a young man trying
to break into it in New York,

00:10:29.855 --> 00:10:32.230
I thought, well, how am I
going to get my name out there?

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:33.830
I might do one or two big jobs.

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:35.420
But then it might
just fade away.

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:35.970
This is new.

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:37.580
This is novel.

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:39.891
And this is really
pre-Instagram, pre-Facebook,

00:10:39.891 --> 00:10:41.890
pre a lot of everything
that anyone was used to,

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:43.450
really pre the internet,
to some extent.

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:44.810
I mean, it was obviously there.

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:47.380
But it was very early days.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:50.080
Yet I kind of always
liked the idea

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:53.290
that we could crack open the
doors of the fashion industry

00:10:53.290 --> 00:10:56.080
and open it to people so they
could see really how it worked.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:57.650
It had changed my life.

00:10:57.650 --> 00:11:00.760
I had found a place where
I wasn't being questioned

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:02.830
about where I was from,
why I looked different,

00:11:02.830 --> 00:11:04.350
why I liked fashion.

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:04.945
Was I gay?

00:11:04.945 --> 00:11:05.570
Was I straight?

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:06.790
None of that mattered.

00:11:06.790 --> 00:11:09.790
It had to do with my talent
and who I was as a person.

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:12.410
And I felt that other people
should learn about that

00:11:12.410 --> 00:11:13.680
and should find out about it.

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:15.430
And that the fashion
industry is, in fact,

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:18.030
a place where there's a
lot of misfits and people

00:11:18.030 --> 00:11:20.760
who had a difficult
childhood who find themselves

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:22.886
in the fashion industry,
and they find a home there

00:11:22.886 --> 00:11:24.968
because they're not judged
for any of those things

00:11:24.968 --> 00:11:25.930
I just mentioned.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:27.864
And that, I thought,
was important.

00:11:27.864 --> 00:11:29.280
And I like that
about "Top Model."

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:33.920
And, hey, it went on from being
a small show to being a cult

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:36.650
phenomenon, that we
were in 146 countries,

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:39.850
with a weekly viewership
of over 100 million people

00:11:39.850 --> 00:11:41.220
watching the show.

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:42.846
It became the largest
television export

00:11:42.846 --> 00:11:44.220
out of the United
States, beating

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:45.565
"Sesame Street" and "Baywatch."

00:11:45.565 --> 00:11:47.240
So there you go.

00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:48.027
Watch out.

00:11:48.027 --> 00:11:49.610
MATT TARGETT: Sorry,
David Hasselhoff.

00:11:49.610 --> 00:11:51.790
NIGEL BARKER: Grover.

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:54.094
MATT TARGETT: So you spoke
about diversity before.

00:11:54.094 --> 00:11:55.260
That's important in fashion.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:58.020
Obviously, a big topic,
and those companies

00:11:58.020 --> 00:12:00.670
are doing it well and
really reaping the benefits.

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:03.280
Amongst your 1.2 million
followers on Google+,

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:08.580
how have you built your
brand in today's world right?

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:11.540
You mentioned TV was the
only outlet back then.

00:12:11.540 --> 00:12:13.570
Now you have so
many more outlets

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:14.899
and mediums to consider.

00:12:14.899 --> 00:12:15.940
NIGEL BARKER: Absolutely.

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:18.191
I think that ultimately what
the most important thing,

00:12:18.191 --> 00:12:19.606
and I think one
of the reasons why

00:12:19.606 --> 00:12:21.620
I was somewhat well-positioned
to take advantage

00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:23.650
of social media,
is that if you're

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:25.869
going to be successful
on reality television,

00:12:25.869 --> 00:12:28.160
and it's one of the reasons
why I think certain reality

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:32.880
shows don't work, is because of
the authenticity of the cast.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.870
And that one of the reasons why
"Top Model" was a huge success

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:40.970
is that when Tyra asked me to
come on, I was nobody, really.

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:42.070
I mean, I was me.

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:43.320
And I was a photographer.

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:44.410
And I was her friend.

00:12:44.410 --> 00:12:46.530
And I did what I did.

00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:47.670
But that's all.

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:49.800
And I think that was
also the genius of her

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:51.127
casting me to be that part.

00:12:51.127 --> 00:12:52.710
She could have found
someone, perhaps,

00:12:52.710 --> 00:12:56.090
who was better known or more
of a television personality.

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:58.570
But, likewise, with
Miss J and Jay Manuel

00:12:58.570 --> 00:13:00.480
and all the other
people she involved,

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:02.800
they were really here
makeup artist, the person

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:04.200
who taught her to walk around.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:05.400
They were the real deal.

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:07.102
Everyone did that job.

00:13:07.102 --> 00:13:09.310
And I think that oftentimes
in reality television now

00:13:09.310 --> 00:13:12.130
you'll find judges and
people who are famous

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:15.340
and they're already a celebrity.

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:17.480
That doesn't really
resonate in the long term.

00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:21.780
And I felt that our
truthfulness and reality worked.

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:23.500
And that also works
in social media.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:26.880
And I've always applied
that, as in, who am I?

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:27.779
What am I about?

00:13:27.779 --> 00:13:30.320
And that is the message that I
put out there on social media.

00:13:30.320 --> 00:13:32.760
So if it's my family, if
it's about my emotion,

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:35.750
if it's about something I
see, some advice I have,

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.570
I give it freely and openly.

00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:40.610
And I don't try and kind of
wrap it or produce it or make it

00:13:40.610 --> 00:13:42.330
look extra glossy or anything.

00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:44.410
It has to have all
the reality behind it.

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:46.250
And I think that
the good reality

00:13:46.250 --> 00:13:47.860
shows, like a "Top
Model," were all

00:13:47.860 --> 00:13:49.760
about the behind the
scenes, which is really

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.680
what so much of social
media is based on

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:55.450
is the behind the scenes
and that learning process.

00:13:55.450 --> 00:13:57.550
So we were already kind
of plugged into that.

00:13:57.550 --> 00:14:01.067
And that's helped me regardless
of whether I understand all

00:14:01.067 --> 00:14:02.150
social media, and I don't.

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:03.733
Have the time, I'm
completely confused

00:14:03.733 --> 00:14:06.140
by how these things work and
why they do what they do.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:07.400
But I do love the interaction.

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:10.219
And I've always been
fascinated in people.

00:14:10.219 --> 00:14:11.260
MATT TARGETT: Absolutely.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:13.950
So how do you stay authentic
in today's day and age?

00:14:13.950 --> 00:14:15.800
I noticed the other
foundations you

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:19.330
work with are largely align
with who you are as a person.

00:14:19.330 --> 00:14:21.770
And why did you
choose Make-A-Wish?

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:23.540
NIGEL BARKER: I didn't
choose Make-A-Wish.

00:14:23.540 --> 00:14:27.910
I think the reality is
Make-A-Wish chose me.

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:30.480
And I think that's the
thing about Make-A-Wish.

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:32.240
Make-A-Wish chooses everybody.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:35.270
And one of the wonderful
things about the Make-A-Wish

00:14:35.270 --> 00:14:39.470
Foundation is that when
you're asked to grant a wish,

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:43.690
you inadvertently have
your own wish granted.

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:45.590
And it's a wish that
you didn't realize

00:14:45.590 --> 00:14:47.337
you wanted to have granted.

00:14:47.337 --> 00:14:48.670
It's sort of the weirdest thing.

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:50.190
When I first got
asked, there I was.

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:51.940
I was on this television
show. "Top Model"

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:53.040
is being super successful.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:55.950
And this young girl, her wish
was to be a model for the day.

00:14:55.950 --> 00:14:58.090
And she knew of me because
she watched the show.

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:01.355
And if she could have this
wish, who better for her

00:15:01.355 --> 00:15:03.860
at that moment then to have the
guy from the television show

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:05.290
take the picture?

00:15:05.290 --> 00:15:06.590
That was the guy she knew.

00:15:06.590 --> 00:15:08.289
And I was honored
enough to be asked.

00:15:08.289 --> 00:15:09.330
It was as simple as that.

00:15:09.330 --> 00:15:11.960
And I thought, sure, I'll
do it-- very flippant,

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:12.970
a bit really.

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:14.650
I was young and excited
about everything

00:15:14.650 --> 00:15:15.941
that was going on in my career.

00:15:15.941 --> 00:15:18.740
I really didn't
understand the full impact

00:15:18.740 --> 00:15:20.260
this was going to have on me.

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:21.909
And I say this
because it was one

00:15:21.909 --> 00:15:23.450
of those extraordinary
moments, Matt,

00:15:23.450 --> 00:15:27.740
where I had this young girl
who'd flown in to New York.

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:29.760
She'd had all the star
treatment of staying

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:31.870
in a wonderful hotel, and
she'd been flown over.

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:34.130
And a limo had taken
her to the studio.

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:36.230
We're shooting in
this wonderful space.

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:37.130
She's excited.

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:39.550
She's only all of 13 years old.

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:43.400
She had had a type of cancer
and multiple operations,

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:44.790
and her arm was all shriveled.

00:15:44.790 --> 00:15:46.900
And she was an
incredible character.

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:49.480
But one half of her body was
all really, kind of deformed

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:50.370
and withered away.

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:51.856
And the other half
seemed normal.

00:15:51.856 --> 00:15:54.230
And I remember her standing
in front of me in this dress.

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:57.750
And she stood there with her arm
all withered, and there's me,

00:15:57.750 --> 00:16:00.760
the photographer, thinking,
OK, I see this withered arm.

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:02.990
I see the other side
looking perfect.

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:05.050
Let me take a couple
of frames of her here.

00:16:05.050 --> 00:16:07.634
Then I'll turn her around, and
we'll get the perfect shot.

00:16:07.634 --> 00:16:09.800
She let me take a couple
of frames of her like that.

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:13.250
Then I said, OK, Nicole,
would you turn around?

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:16.529
And she looked at me, and she
said, I don't really want to.

00:16:16.529 --> 00:16:19.070
And I sort of smiled and said,
oh, well, we've got this side.

00:16:19.070 --> 00:16:20.260
Let's get the other side.

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:22.020
But she was very savvy.

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:24.070
And she looked at me
straight in the eyes.

00:16:24.070 --> 00:16:25.050
I remember to this day.

00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:26.466
It's down the
barrel of my lenses,

00:16:26.466 --> 00:16:31.210
these beautiful blue eyes,
deep and they were sad,

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:33.340
but they were positive,
and they were confident,

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:34.460
and they were real.

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:36.251
And she looked to me
and said, do you know?

00:16:36.251 --> 00:16:37.410
I don't want to.

00:16:37.410 --> 00:16:39.550
This is why I'm here.

00:16:39.550 --> 00:16:42.360
This is my story.

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:43.920
This is a part of me.

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:45.940
And it was a defining moment.

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:48.190
Here I am, a man
who defined himself

00:16:48.190 --> 00:16:51.640
by searching for beauty,
telling people what was pretty,

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:53.850
what was not, how to be a
model, all the rest of it.

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:55.770
And a little girl
of 14 years old

00:16:55.770 --> 00:16:58.850
made me see for the first
time what true beauty was.

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:00.990
The courage, the
bravery in that moment

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:04.440
alone redefined my
concept of beauty,

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:08.649
and it set me on a
trip forever after,

00:17:08.649 --> 00:17:12.640
of searching for that kind of
person, that kind of beauty.

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:15.494
In the films that I
filmed and the charities

00:17:15.494 --> 00:17:17.910
I've been involved with, it's
about those kinds of people.

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:19.599
That they move me,
and they're the ones

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:22.250
who make me fall
in love with people

00:17:22.250 --> 00:17:26.349
and life and the potential.

00:17:26.349 --> 00:17:27.849
And she became a
lifelong friend.

00:17:27.849 --> 00:17:33.050
I was incredibly in
awe of this young girl,

00:17:33.050 --> 00:17:34.320
and I followed her career.

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:39.040
And in fact, when she went to
college and she went to Parsons

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:41.580
and she graduated, I actually
collaborated with her

00:17:41.580 --> 00:17:43.850
on her first exhibition,
where I put her art

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:44.704
into my photographs.

00:17:44.704 --> 00:17:47.120
And we did a show in New York
City, which she opened with.

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:50.249
And we did a complete
sold-out show of all her work,

00:17:50.249 --> 00:17:51.165
and it was phenomenal.

00:17:52.410 --> 00:17:55.514
And for me, my wish is being
granted over and over again.

00:17:55.514 --> 00:17:57.930
And I've noticed that with
everybody who I've got involved

00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:01.950
is that you won't believe how
life changing Make-A-Wish is

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:03.790
for everybody involved.

00:18:03.790 --> 00:18:06.420
And it takes a village
to do these wishes.

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:07.604
It's not a one-man a band.

00:18:07.604 --> 00:18:08.895
MATT TARGETT: Yeah, absolutely.

00:18:08.895 --> 00:18:10.019
I was going to get to that.

00:18:10.019 --> 00:18:12.470
There's a lot of volunteers
behind the scenes.

00:18:12.470 --> 00:18:14.040
People obviously
donate their money

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:16.120
and also donate airline miles.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:19.474
I know United Airlines is
offering a donation match.

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:20.760
NIGEL BARKER: Absolutely.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:22.426
MATT TARGETT: You
said it takes an army,

00:18:22.426 --> 00:18:25.530
and summer is the busiest
time for Make-A-Wish.

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:27.140
Can you go over that for a sec?

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:28.850
NIGEL BARKER:
Absolutely, well, there's

00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:31.691
no doubt that summer
is obviously, as far as

00:18:31.691 --> 00:18:33.690
weather-related and
everything else, the summers

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:34.898
are always an important time.

00:18:34.898 --> 00:18:38.360
And of course, kids are out
of school and more available.

00:18:38.360 --> 00:18:40.850
And parents tend to perhaps
have vacation time and things

00:18:40.850 --> 00:18:41.350
like that.

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:45.130
So there's a realness to the
actual timing of these things.

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:47.990
And there's a campaign
that Make-A-Wish

00:18:47.990 --> 00:18:49.600
has called Wishes Can't Wait.

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:52.755
And there's a couple of things
about Make-A-Wish, first

00:18:52.755 --> 00:18:54.380
of all, that I'd just
like to say, too.

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:57.280
That people often
think that the children

00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:02.510
who are having their wishes
granted have terminal illness.

00:19:02.510 --> 00:19:03.957
Sometimes that's the case.

00:19:03.957 --> 00:19:05.540
But it's not the
story of Make-A-Wish.

00:19:05.540 --> 00:19:06.966
Make-A-Wish is
about children with

00:19:06.966 --> 00:19:08.090
life-threatening illnesses.

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:12.910
And reality is that many times
the actual wishes themselves--

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:15.420
and this is what doctors have
said over and over again--

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:18.140
have given the children
a sense of hope,

00:19:18.140 --> 00:19:19.780
an ability to dream,
like you heard

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:21.950
of this young girl who
was talking just now,

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:23.590
that wishes do come true.

00:19:23.590 --> 00:19:27.430
And when you live a life
from an early age of pain,

00:19:27.430 --> 00:19:30.170
suffering, medication,
hospital visits, you often

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:32.260
don't know what it
means to be a child.

00:19:32.260 --> 00:19:34.750
You don't realize what it's
like to wish and to dream

00:19:34.750 --> 00:19:36.470
and to fantasize about
what could happen

00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:38.010
or what the future's
going to look like.

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:39.990
And all of a sudden, when
you experience something

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:41.781
like this young girl
did of going to Google

00:19:41.781 --> 00:19:44.870
and seeing how you live and
what you're doing for the world,

00:19:44.870 --> 00:19:47.230
and she thinks, goodness,
that could be me.

00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:49.760
I might have a
chance to do that.

00:19:49.760 --> 00:19:52.840
That moment for a
child can give them

00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:56.700
the courage and the enthusiasm
and the wish and the desire

00:19:56.700 --> 00:19:59.470
to actually heal
themselves from within,

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:03.309
and to make the opportunity
and optimism itself.

00:20:03.309 --> 00:20:04.350
It's not a medical thing.

00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:05.266
It's not a medication.

00:20:05.266 --> 00:20:06.640
It's hard to quantify.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:10.480
But doctor after doctor after
doctor have lined up and said,

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:15.205
there is a reason why we refer
our patients to Make-A-Wish.

00:20:15.205 --> 00:20:16.830
It's not just because
we feel that they

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:20.060
should have a fun time, because
it's cute, because it's nice.

00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:22.180
It's because it
actually literally

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:24.040
can turn the patients around.

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:27.007
So the summer is
an important time

00:20:27.007 --> 00:20:28.465
to get activated,
to get motivated.

00:20:28.465 --> 00:20:30.960
And Because some
children, too, it

00:20:30.960 --> 00:20:33.090
might be their only opportunity.

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:36.810
And I feel that we act now.

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:39.310
We act as fast as
you can and don't

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:41.180
wait for someone to
ask you, but to get

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:42.379
involved as soon as you can.

00:20:42.379 --> 00:20:43.420
MATT TARGETT: Absolutely.

00:20:43.420 --> 00:20:46.470
We actually have a video of one
of your wishes being granted

00:20:46.470 --> 00:20:48.304
that was shown at
the Make-A-Wish gala

00:20:48.304 --> 00:20:49.220
The Power of the Wish.

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:50.261
Can we show that, please?

00:20:50.261 --> 00:20:51.606
NIGEL BARKER: Show it, please.

00:20:51.606 --> 00:20:52.272
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:52.272 --> 00:20:55.080
-I've been shooting wishes with
Make-A-Wish now for 10 years.

00:20:55.080 --> 00:20:56.890
And I've seen
firsthand what a wish

00:20:56.890 --> 00:21:00.410
can do for a child battling
a life-threatening illness.

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:03.600
It can heal their spirit,
give them strength to fight,

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:06.506
