for information and donations

00:35:12.350 --> 00:35:12.880
as well.

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:17.100
So there's 350,000 wishes
granted worldwide, right?

00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:18.600
Are there any that
stand out to you?

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:20.980
I think everyone's heard
of that Bat Kid and SF.

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:22.955
But are there are any
that are lesser known?

00:35:22.955 --> 00:35:24.580
NIGEL BARKER: I think
one of the things

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:26.480
that I find fascinating is,
listen, there's definitely

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:27.700
that big wishes, right?

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:30.140
There these fantastic
over-the-top wishes,

00:35:30.140 --> 00:35:32.480
like in Chicago and
they shut the city down,

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:34.300
and everyone gets
involved, and it's

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:39.950
super glamorous and over the
top, and you're like, wow.

00:35:39.950 --> 00:35:41.430
And that wish is fantastic.

00:35:41.430 --> 00:35:42.710
It's obviously great
for press, and everyone

00:35:42.710 --> 00:35:44.780
gets to hear about it, and
the kid has this amazing wish,

00:35:44.780 --> 00:35:46.300
and other kids are
like, wow, that's cool,

00:35:46.300 --> 00:35:47.670
and they hear about Make-A-Wish.

00:35:47.670 --> 00:35:49.044
That's the wonderful
thing there.

00:35:49.044 --> 00:35:53.290
But what for me, what I found
fascinating about Make-A-Wish,

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:56.490
and the wishes in general,
is that the children are just

00:35:56.490 --> 00:35:57.370
children.

00:35:57.370 --> 00:36:01.530
And what they wish for
is very specific to them,

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:03.450
and they're not always massive.

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:06.250
Children come from all
different walks of life.

00:36:06.250 --> 00:36:08.042
And some of them
have these dreams

00:36:08.042 --> 00:36:09.750
because they're into
a superhero and they

00:36:09.750 --> 00:36:11.090
want to be a superhero.

00:36:11.090 --> 00:36:14.360
But others, their wishes
can be very simple.

00:36:14.360 --> 00:36:15.950
And I've known of
wishes where kids

00:36:15.950 --> 00:36:18.840
have wanted to go to a farm to
touch an animal because they

00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:21.230
live in an urban environment,
and they've never actually

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:22.050
been to a farm.

00:36:22.050 --> 00:36:24.120
And they've only ever
seen sort of animals

00:36:24.120 --> 00:36:28.251
on television or in a book or
on the shelves of a supermarket,

00:36:28.251 --> 00:36:28.750
literally.

00:36:28.750 --> 00:36:29.833
And they would like to go.

00:36:29.833 --> 00:36:32.440
Or they want to go to the
beach and feel the water

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:34.650
between their toes in the sand.

00:36:34.650 --> 00:36:37.230
And you're like,
that's your wish?

00:36:37.230 --> 00:36:39.630
It's just to go to the beach?

00:36:39.630 --> 00:36:41.000
But I don't belittle it.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.100
The reality is that
for that child,

00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:46.020
they've never seen a horizon.

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:48.620
They've lived in
hospital rooms, where

00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:52.850
they've only ever seen a wall
and a TV that's in the thing.

00:36:52.850 --> 00:36:55.220
And for them, all
of a sudden, just

00:36:55.220 --> 00:36:58.814
to see the sunset on the
water and to hear the water

00:36:58.814 --> 00:37:00.480
and to see the sand,
it's only something

00:37:00.480 --> 00:37:02.130
they've seen in a film.

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:04.890
Then you realize that that
is a beautiful moment,

00:37:04.890 --> 00:37:06.550
yet it could be life
changing for them.

00:37:06.550 --> 00:37:07.920
And we take it for granted.

00:37:07.920 --> 00:37:10.290
Those wishes, I think,
are so powerful.

00:37:10.290 --> 00:37:12.860
And they're no less powerful
than the big wishes, which

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:15.430
is, again, the reason why
we all have the opportunity

00:37:15.430 --> 00:37:16.110
to get involved.

00:37:16.110 --> 00:37:18.360
Sometimes when you see
these gigantic wishes,

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:21.530
you're like, well, heck, I
couldn't have pulled that off.

00:37:21.530 --> 00:37:24.352
But there are things you can
do that can make a difference.

00:37:24.352 --> 00:37:26.810
GINA FLORESCU: There was a
great wish that we had recently.

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:30.110
It does embody sort of
what children go through

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:32.350
and how they're actually
trying to come up

00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:34.570
with a wish that
really comes out

00:37:34.570 --> 00:37:36.175
of their creativity and heart.

00:37:36.175 --> 00:37:37.550
Because we're a
New York City, we

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:38.966
do what are called
"wish assists."

00:37:38.966 --> 00:37:42.610
So other chapters who are
coming, who have wishes,

00:37:42.610 --> 00:37:44.860
they come to New York
and we assist them.

00:37:44.860 --> 00:37:46.840
This kid wanted
to ride elevators.

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:48.860
It was elevators and
push elevator buttons.

00:37:48.860 --> 00:37:50.900
And the genesis is,
to a certain degree,

00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:52.887
because he'd always
been in hospitals.

00:37:52.887 --> 00:37:54.720
And he always wanted
to touch those buttons.

00:37:54.720 --> 00:37:56.430
And he's lying down.

00:37:56.430 --> 00:38:00.320
He can see the exit signs, and
his world was very different.

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:02.090
He was a nonverbal kid.

00:38:02.090 --> 00:38:03.730
But this is what
he wanted to do.

00:38:03.730 --> 00:38:06.590
So they set up this
brilliant wish.

00:38:06.590 --> 00:38:10.590
Macy's let him in
before it opened,

00:38:10.590 --> 00:38:12.350
and they let him
click the switch that

00:38:12.350 --> 00:38:16.500
started those old wooden
escalators going up the middle.

00:38:16.500 --> 00:38:18.287
He'd had never seen
anything like it.

00:38:18.287 --> 00:38:20.620
And then he took some of the
different elevators around.

00:38:20.620 --> 00:38:22.650
And then there was
the freight elevator,

00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:25.930
where he's standing there,
and it opens up sideways.

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:28.800
And there's this man
standing in there,

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:32.597
and this kid was so enamored,
like I said, he was non-verbal,

00:38:32.597 --> 00:38:34.430
but at the end, he sort
of made this motion.

00:38:34.430 --> 00:38:36.660
And his mom said,
oh, he wants a hug.

00:38:36.660 --> 00:38:40.760
So this big elevator operator
who had no idea what his day

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:43.410
was going to be like when
he walked in that day,

00:38:43.410 --> 00:38:45.490
you know he's never
going to forget that.

00:38:45.490 --> 00:38:45.810
NIGEL BARKER: He was a hero.

00:38:45.810 --> 00:38:47.018
GINA FLORESCU: He was a hero.

00:38:47.018 --> 00:38:51.240
